{"add":{"doc":{"id":"7a97290efb39f7653cd42b83430818ee0f660e219ae7a7a54048be4ac48c508f","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/RP_vowel_movement.png/350px-RP_vowel_movement.png","previous":["Like all accents, RP has changed with time. For example, sound recordings and films from the first half of the 20th century demonstrate that it was usual for speakers of RP to pronounce the /æ/ sound, as in land, with a vowel close to [ɛ], so that land would sound similar to a present-day pronunciation of lend. RP is sometimes known as the Queen's English, but recordings show that even Queen Elizabeth II has changed her pronunciation over the past 50 years, no longer using an [ɛ]-like vowel in words like land.[80]"],"after":["Some changes in RP during the 20th century include:"]}}}